     <h2>SSDI vs. SSI: what is the difference?</h2>
     <p>Both programs provide financial support for people unable to work due to disability, but they have different eligibility rules. Learn more from the <a href="https://www.ssa.gov/benefits/disability/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Social Security Administration</a>:</p>
     <div class="overflow-x-auto rounded-xl border border-zinc-200 my-6 not-prose"><table class="w-full text-sm"><thead><tr class="bg-accent-light/50"><th class="py-3 px-4 text-left font-semibold text-zinc-900">Feature</th><th class="py-3 px-4 text-left font-semibold text-zinc-900">SSDI</th><th class="py-3 px-4 text-left font-semibold text-zinc-900">SSI</th></tr></thead><tbody class="text-zinc-600"><tr class="border-t border-zinc-100"><td class="py-2.5 px-4 font-semibold text-zinc-900">Based on</td><td class="py-2.5 px-4">Work credits and payroll taxes paid</td><td class="py-2.5 px-4">Financial need (limited income and assets)</td></tr><tr class="border-t border-zinc-100"><td class="py-2.5 px-4 font-semibold text-zinc-900">Medical requirement</td><td class="py-2.5 px-4" colspan="2">Same: disability prevents substantial gainful activity</td></tr><tr class="border-t border-zinc-100"><td class="py-2.5 px-4 font-semibold text-zinc-900">Health insurance</td><td class="py-2.5 px-4">Medicare after 24 months</td><td class="py-2.5 px-4">Medicaid (in most states)</td></tr></tbody></table></div>
 
     <h2>The SSA listing for ADHD</h2>
     <p>The SSA evaluates ADHD under Listing 112.11 (for children) and in adult claims under mental disorder listings. For adults, ADHD is typically evaluated under <strong>Listing 12.11</strong> (neurodevelopmental disorders). To qualify, you must demonstrate:</p>
     <ul><li><strong>Medical documentation</strong> of ADHD diagnosis with symptoms of hyperactivity, impulsivity, and/or inattention</li><li><strong>Marked limitation</strong> in at least two of: understanding and applying information, interacting with others, concentrating and maintaining pace, adapting and managing oneself</li><li>Or the ADHD must be "serious and persistent" with a documented history over at least 2 years</li></ul>
 
     <h2>Why ADHD-only claims face challenges</h2>
     <p>The SSA often denies claims where ADHD is the only condition. Here is why:</p>
     <h3>Inconsistent functional impact</h3>
     <p>Many people with ADHD hold jobs and function in daily life, even if they struggle significantly. The SSA looks for conditions that prevent <strong>any</strong> substantial gainful activity, not just the job you left.</p>
     <h3>Symptoms can be managed</h3>
     <p>ADHD symptoms can improve with medication and coping strategies. The SSA may argue that treatment reduces the severity, making it harder to prove total disability.</p>
     <h3>Documentation is subjective</h3>
     <p>Unlike physical disabilities with clear test results, ADHD relies on observational evidence, self-reports, and clinician judgment. This makes it harder to meet the SSA's bar for "objective medical evidence."</p>
     <h3>Symptoms fluctuate</h3>
     <p>ADHD symptoms vary in intensity day to day, making "consistent and severe" hard to prove over the required 12-month period.</p>
     <p class="mt-4">Claims are more likely to succeed when ADHD is combined with other diagnosed conditions such as anxiety, depression, learning disabilities, or other mental health conditions.</p>
 
     <h2>How to strengthen your claim</h2>
     <h3>Medical records and testing</h3>
     <p>Include physician notes, neuropsychological testing results, medication history, and therapy notes. A comprehensive evaluation carries more weight than a brief doctor's note.</p>
     <h3>Work history evidence</h3>
     <p>Collect performance reviews, disciplinary records, and job termination letters that document ADHD-related work difficulties. A detailed function report describing how ADHD affects your daily activities is essential.</p>
     <h3>Third-party statements</h3>
     <p>Letters from supervisors, coworkers, or family members describing your limitations can corroborate your own account and strengthen your case.</p>
     <h3>Get legal representation</h3>
     <p>SSDI attorneys work on contingency -- they only get paid if you win. Legal representation significantly improves your odds, especially at the hearing stage. About 67% of initial applications are denied, but approval rates increase dramatically with representation at the Administrative Law Judge level.</p>
 
     <h2>What to expect from the process</h2>
     <div class="callout-accent p-6 my-8 not-prose"><p class="font-bold text-zinc-900 text-lg mb-2">Prepare for a long process</p><p class="text-sm text-zinc-600 leading-relaxed">Be ready for a process that can take 12-24 months. Most approvals come at the Administrative Law Judge hearing stage, not the initial application. Do not give up after the first denial -- it is expected. Continue medical treatment and keep building your evidence throughout the appeals process.</p></div>
